{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8f3018cdc5afd46c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tQuaSR: Quality-Aware Sample Reweighting for\n2\tPacific Indigenous Speech Recognition\n3\tYishun Li∗ , Yang Xiao∗ , Gongping Huang† , Eun-Jung Holden∗ , Nick Thieberger∗ , Ting Dang∗\n4\t∗ The University of Melbourne, Australia\n5\t\n6\tarXiv:2607.03658v1 [eess.AS] 4 Jul 2026\n7\t\n8\t† Wuhan University, China\n9\t\n10\tAbstract—Training automatic speech recognition (ASR) models\n11\tfor low-resource languages is challenging due to limited data\n12\tand highly variable supervision quality. In particular, Pacific\n13\tIndigenous speech corpora often exhibit heterogeneous acoustic\n14\tconditions, transcript inconsistencies, and varying degrees of\n15\tacoustic–text alignment reliability, making standard fine-tuning\n16\tapproaches sensitive to noisy or misleading supervision signals.\n17\tIn this work, we propose QuaSR, a simple yet effective weighting\n18\tframework that combines data-side reliability with model-side\n19\tlearnability to improve ASR adaptation. Specifically, we estimate\n20\tdata reliability from acoustic, transcription, and alignment, while\n21\tmeasuring learnability using training loss from the model. These\n22\ttwo complementary signals are integrated into a unified sample\n23\tutility score to produce training weights for the samples. We also\n24\tevaluated across four Pacific Indigenous languages, which shows\n25\tthat the proposed utility scores reliably correlate with adaptation\n26\tperformance. Furthermore, QuaSR consistently improves ASR\n27\tadaptation over standard fine-tuning and alternative data selection\n28\tstrategies, highlighting a new way to leverage difficulty scores for\n29\tlow-resource speech learning.\n30\tIndex Terms—low-resource ASR, Sample Reweighting , Vanuatu\n31\tlanguages, data quality, Whisper adaptation\n32\t\n33\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n34\tAutomatic speech recognition (ASR) has achieved substantial\n35\timprovements on high-resource language benchmarks in recent\n36\tyears [1]–[3]. However, these advances remain unevenly\n37\tdistributed across the world’s languages. For many low-resource\n38\tlanguages, the primary bottleneck is not model capacity but\n39\tthe limited availability of suitable speech data for adaptation\n40\tand evaluation. Collecting and annotating speech corpora\n41\tis costly and time-consuming, and available recordings are\n42\toften sourced from linguistic documentation projects, field\n43\trecordings, or archival collections rather than speech datasets\n44\tspecifically designed for ASR [4]. Pacific Indigenous languages\n45\texemplify this challenge: available data are often limited in\n46\tscale, heterogeneous in recording conditions, and inconsistent\n47\tin transcription quality and segmentation. Consequently, these\n48\tresources are often poorly matched to the assumptions of\n49\tmodern end-to-end ASR systems, which generally perform best\n50\twith large quantities of consistently segmented and transcribed\n51\tspeech [5]. Due to the resource challenge, it is difficult to train\n52\tan ASR model from scratch for Pacific Indigenous languages.\n53\tWith the notable zero-shot performance with speech foundation models (SFM), recent work has begun exploring parameterefficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods to adapt SFM to lowresource languages. Whilst these approaches have demonstrated\n54\t\n55\ta degree of effectiveness, performance on Pacific Indigenous\n56\tlanguages remains consistently below that of better-resourced\n57\tlanguages, and varies considerably even across Pacific languages themselves [5], [6]. This disparity is most likely\n58\tattributable to the extremely limited data volume available\n59\tfor these languages and, more critically, to fundamental issues\n60\tof data quality when collecting the Pacific Indigenous languages\n61\tdata.\n62\tCollecting speech data from Pacific Indigenous communities\n63\tpresents significant practical challenges. Recording conditions\n64\tare rarely controlled, resulting in substantial acoustic variability\n65\tand background noise. Transcription poses an equally serious\n66\tobstacle: accurate annotation requires access to community\n67\tlanguage experts, who are few in number and whose availability\n68\tis often constrained [4], [7]–[9]. Consequently, transcriptions\n69\tmay be incomplete, inconsistent, or of uncertain reliability, a\n70\tproblem that is compounded when the underlying recordings\n71\tare themselves of poor quality. Interestingly, recent work has\n72\tfound that adaptation performance is not purely determined by\n73\tdata volume [5], [6], suggesting that data quality may play an\n74\tequally, if not more, consequential role. While model adaptation\n75\tis fundamentally bounded by the quality of the data on which\n76\tit relies, it is therefore essential to systematically investigate\n77\tdata quality as a factor shaping adaptation performance, and to\n78\tleverage data-centric insights to better understand and improve\n79\tASR for Pacific Indigenous languages [10].\n80\tWe formalize data quality in Pacific Indigenous ASR\n81\tas multi-dimensional, comprising i) acoustic quality, which\n82\treflects the intelligibility and signal fidelity of the recording\n83\tunder variable recording conditions, ii) transcript stability,\n84\twhich captures visible transcription irregularities in the written\n85\ttarget, and iii) audio–text alignment quality, which reflects\n86\twhether the recording and transcript correspond at the utterance\n87\tand word levels. Prior work has studied acoustic quality\n88\tvia reference-less speech intelligibility estimation [11], [12],\n89\ttranscript quality in field-linguistic corpora [4], and audio–text\n90\talignment using multilingual resources that make broad forcedalignment diagnostics feasible [2]. However, these signals\n91\tare usually considered separately, reflecting only partial data\n92\tquality. Moreover, for Pacific Indigenous ASR adaptation,\n93\tidentifying the relevant data-quality dimension is important for\n94\tthree reasons. First, from a data-centric perspective, it helps\n95\tidentify potential directions for data collection and guide the\n96\tconstruction of a more suitable dataset under the same resource\n97\t\n98\t\fconstraint. Second, it helps examine how data quality affects\n99\tASR adaptation of Pacific Indigenous languages.\n100\tadaptation performance and informs the design of effective\n101\t• Experimental results across four languages demonstrate\n102\tPEFT methods that utilize all valuable data. Third, for training\n103\tthe effectiveness of QuaSR in the adaptation process,\n104\tmethods such as sample reweighting, data quality can serve as\n105\tproviding a generalized scoring framework applicable to\n106\ta core metric for reweighting training examples and improving\n107\tother low-resource languages.\n108\tadaptation performance.\n109\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n110\tCurriculum learning (CL) serves as a highly effective\n111\tparadigm for domain adaptation, particularly when the training A. ASR Adaptation for Pacific Indigenous Languages\n112\tcorpus exhibits high data quality heterogeneity [13], [14]. By\n113\tRecent work has begun adapting large pretrained speech\n114\tprogressively exposing the model to samples of increasing com- models to Pacific Indigenous languages, demonstrating that fineplexity, CL smooths the optimization landscape and prevents tuning is feasible even under severely limited data conditions\n115\tpremature convergence to poor local minima caused by noisy [5], [6]. However, recognition performance varies considerably\n116\tor out-of-domain utterances [13]. Rather than scheduling an across languages even under comparable model configurations,\n117\teasy-to-hard ordering, we adopt the reweighting instantiation and the sources of this variability remain poorly understood [5],\n118\tof this idea: we tran