rrespondence\n218\tbetween the acoustic signal and its transcript [2]. Multilingual resources such as MMS make such forced-alignment\n219\tdiagnostics feasible across many low-resource languages [2].\n220\tWhilst each of these dimensions has been studied independently\n221\tand provides useful evidence in its own right, they are rarely\n222\tconsidered jointly, leaving a gap in our understanding of how\n223\ttheir combination shapes data reliability. More importantly, how\n224\tthese dimensions can be collectively applied to estimate data\n225\tquality for Pacific Indigenous languages, and subsequently\n226\tleveraged to improve ASR adaptation, remains an open\n227\tquestion. These three dimensions together motivate a more\n228\tcomprehensive and principled picture of data quality for lowresource ASR adaptation.\n229\tIII. PACIFIC I NDIGENOUS S PEECH C ORPUS\n230\t\n231\t(A). The model-side learnability term is estimated from samplelevel loss values recorded during an unweighted baseline\n232\ttraining run. QuaSR multiplies these two terms so that a\n233\tsample receives high training influence only when it is both\n234\treliable in data quality and learnable for the current model.\n235\tThe resulting sample utility is then incorporated in a soft loss\n236\tweight for LoRA adaptation.\n237\tA. Data Reliability\n238\tData-side reliability estimates whether an utterance is a\n239\thigh-quality sample suitable for reliable supervision by capturing three complementary dimensions. Acoustic quality (Q),\n240\testimated using the SQUIM estimate of short-time objective\n241\tintelligibility (STOI), measures whether the speech signal is\n242\tsufficiently intelligible for ASR training [11], [12]. Transcript\n243\tstability (T ) measures visible transcription irregularities in the\n244\ttranscript, including markers of incomplete transcription, digit\n245\tcharacters, and isolated non-lexical symbols. Audio–text alignment reliability (A), estimated from MMS forced-alignment\n