\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "0286849f-2735-4e25-a315-d5258203a671", "uuid": "7d324a31-cae5-4fb8-99ae-ead52b8f353a", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T11:06:52.866Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/quaSR.txt", "content": "QuaSR: Quality-Aware Sample Reweighting for\nPacific Indigenous Speech Recognition\nYishun Li∗ , Yang Xiao∗ , Gongping Huang† , Eun-Jung Holden∗ , Nick Thieberger∗ , Ting Dang∗\n∗ The University of Melbourne, Australia\n\narXiv:2607.03658v1 [eess.AS] 4 Jul 2026\n\n† Wuhan University, China\n\nAbstract—Training automatic speech recognition (ASR) models\nfor low-resource languages is challenging due to limited data\nand highly variable supervision quality. In particular, Pacific\nIndigenous speech corpora often exhibit heterogeneous acoustic\nconditions, transcript inconsistencies, and varying degrees of\nacoustic–text alignment reliability, making standard fine-tuning\napproaches sensitive to noisy or misleading supervision signals.\nIn this work, we propose QuaSR, a simple yet effective weighting\nframework that combines data-side reliability with model-side\nlearnability to improve ASR adaptation. Specifically, we estimate\ndata reliability from acoustic, transcription, and alignment, while\nmeasuring learnability using training loss from the model. These\ntwo complementary signals are integrated into a unified sample\nutility score to produce training weights for the samples. We also\nevaluated across four Pacific Indigenous languages, which shows\nthat the proposed utility scores reliably correlate with adaptation\nperformance. Furthermore, QuaSR consistently improves ASR\nadaptation over standard fine-tuning and alternative data selection\nstrategies, highlighting a new way to leverage difficulty scores for\nlow-resource speech learning.\nIndex Terms—low-resource ASR, Sample Reweighting , Vanuatu\nlanguages, data quality, Whisper adaptation\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nAutomatic speech recognition (ASR) has achieved substantial\nimprovements on high-resource language benchmarks in recent\nyears [1]–[3]. However, these advances remain unevenly\ndistributed across the world’s languages. For many low-resource\nlanguages, the primary bottleneck is not model capacity but\nthe limited availability of suitable speech data for adaptation\nand evaluation. Collecting and annotating speech corpora\nis costly and time-consuming, and available recordings are\noften sourced from linguistic documentation projects, field\nrecordings, or archival collections rather than speech datasets\nspecifically designed for ASR [4]. Pacific Indigenous languages\nexemplify this challenge: available data are often limited in\nscale, heterogeneous in recording conditions, and inconsistent\nin transcription quality and segmentation. Consequently, these\nresources are often poorly matched to the assumptions of\nmodern end-to-end ASR systems, which generally perform best\nwith large quantities of consistently segmented and transcribed\nspeech [5]. Due to the resource challenge, it is difficult to train\nan ASR model from scratch for Pacific Indigenous languages.\nWith the notable zero-shot performance with speech foundation models (SFM), recent work has begun exploring parameterefficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods to adapt SFM to lowresource languages. Whilst these approaches have demonstrated\n\na degree of effectiveness, performance on Pacific Indigenous\nlanguages remains consistently below that of better-resourced\nlanguages, and varies considerably even across Pacific languages themselves [5], [6]. This disparity is most likely\nattributable to the extremely limited data volume available\nfor these languages and, more critically, to fundamental issues\nof data quality when collecting the Pacific Indigenous languages\ndata.\nCollecting speech data from Pacific Indigenous communities\npresents significant practical challenges. Recording conditions\nare rarely controlled, resulting in substantial acoustic variability\nand background noise. Transcription poses an equally serious\nobstacle: accurate annotation requires access to community\nlanguage experts, who are few in number and whose availability\nis often constrained [4], [7]–[9]. Consequently, transcriptions\nmay be incomplete, inconsistent, or of uncertain reliability, a\nproblem that is compounded when the underlying recordings\nare themselves of poor quality. Interestingly, recent work has\nfound that adaptation performance is not purely determined by\ndata volume [5], [6], suggesting that data quality may play an\nequally, if not more, consequential role. While model adaptation\nis fundamentally bounded by the quality of the data on which\nit relies, it is therefore essential to systematically investigate\ndata quality as a factor shaping adaptation performance, and to\nleverage data-centric insights to better understand and improve\nASR for Pacific Indigenous languages [10].\nWe formalize data quality in Pacific Indigenous ASR\nas multi-dimensional, comprising i) acoustic quality, which\nreflects the intelligibility and signal fidelity of the recording\nunder variable recording conditions, ii) transcript stability,\nwhich captures visible transcription irregularities in the written\ntarget, and iii) audio–text alignment quality, which reflects\nwhether the recording and transcript correspond at the utterance\nand word levels. Prior work has studied acoustic quality\nvia reference-less speech intelligibility estimation [11], [12],\ntranscript quality in field-linguistic corpora [4], and audio–text\nalignment using multilingual resources that make broad forcedalignment diagnostics feasible [2]. However, these signals\nare usually considered separately, reflecting only partial data\nquality. Moreover, for Pacific Indigenous ASR adaptation,\nidentifying the relevant data-quality dimension is important for\nthree reasons. First, from a data-centric perspective, it helps\nidentify potential directions for data collection and guide the\nconstruction of a more suitable dataset under the same resource\n\n\fconstraint. Second, it helps examine how data quality affects\nASR adaptation of Pacific Indigenous languages.\nadaptation performance and informs the design of effective\n• Experimental results across four languages demonstrate\nPEFT methods that utilize all valuable data. Third, for training\nthe effectiveness of QuaSR in the adaptation process,\nmethods such as sample reweighting, data quality can serve as\nproviding a generalized scoring framework applicable to\na core metric for reweighting training examples and improving\nother low-resource languages.\nadaptation performance.\nII. R ELATED W ORK\nCurriculum learning (CL) serves as a highly effective\nparadigm for domain adaptation, particularly when the training A. ASR Adaptation for Pacific Indigenous Languages\ncorpus exhibits high data quality heterogeneity [13], [14]. By\nRecent work has begun adapting large pretrained speech\nprogressively exposing the model to samples of increasing com- models to Pacific Indigenous languages, demonstrating that fineplexity, CL smooths the optimization landscape and prevents tuning is feasible even under severely limited data conditions\npremature convergence to poor local minima caused by noisy [5], [6]. However, recognition performance varies considerably\nor out-of-domain utterances [13]. Rather than scheduling an across languages even under comparable model configurations,\neasy-to-hard ordering, we adopt the reweighting instantiation and the sources of this variability remain poorly understood [5],\nof this idea: we translate estimated per-sample difficulty into [6], [17], [18]. Existing studies primarily attribute performance\nfixed loss weights computed before training [15], [16], keeping differences to data volume and language distance, yet neither\nall utterances but scaling their contributions, which provides factor fully explains the observed gaps. A critical missing piece\na natural basis for incorporating data-quality evidence into is data-quality evidence: understanding how acoustic conditions,\nASR adaptation. For Pacific Indigenous languages, model-side transcription reliability, and audio–text alignment jointly shape\ndifficulty estimation alone is insufficient because high loss adaptation outcomes, and how such evidence should inform\ncan be ambiguous. Degraded acoustic quality and misaligned the training process.\ntranscriptions may both lead to high loss, but this often reflects\nnoisy supervision, where the data may be harmful rather than B. Sample Difficulty and Training Dynamics\nThe notion of sample difficulty has been widely used\nrepresenting learnable training difficulty. Therefore, combining\ndata-side reliability with model-side difficulty estimates could in quality-aware training like curriculum learning, which\nprovide a clearer and more effective basis for quality-aware proposes ordering training examples from easier to harder,\nwith difficulty approximated in ASR through proxies such\nreweighting in Pacific Indigenous ASR.\nIn this work, we propose QuaSR (Quality-aware sample as utterance duration, training loss, and model uncertainty\nreweighting), a multi-dimensional data quality scoring frame- [13], [15], [16]. Training-dynamics approaches, such as dataset\nwork for Pacific Indigenous ASR. It further leverages the quality cartography [19], extend this by characterizing examples\nscores with model-based difficulty estimates for improved ASR through model behavior across training epochs rather than static\nadaptation performance. Specifically, QuaSR quantifies data metadata alone, revealing whether examples are consistently\nquality across three complementary dimensions and merges easy, hard, or unstable for the model. However, for noisy\nthem into a single composite quality score. We further calibrate speech corpora such as those found in Pacific Indigenous\nthe model-based difficulty score with this composite score, language collections, high training loss is inherently ambiguous:\nmitigating cases where model-based scores alone conflate noisy it may reflect genuinely learnable linguistic difficulty or, equally,\nsupervision with genuinely informative difficulty. The score unreliable supervision arising from poor acoustics, inconsistent\ntherefore serves a dual role: it provides a data-quality diagnostic transcription, or misaligned audio–text pairs. This ambiguity\nfor analyzing adaptation behavior beyond data volume, and it motivates sample-weighting criteria that explicitly distinguish\nmodel-side learnability from data-side supervision reliability\nprovides a calibration signal for sample weighting.\nQuaSR is validated across four Pacific Indigenous languages: — precisely the gap that QuaSR addresses.\nBislama, Nafsan, Lelepa, and Nguna, and the proposed quality\nC. Speech Corpus Quality\nscores successfully interpret adaptation performance, demonSpeech corpus quality is multi-dimensional, but Pacific\nstrating their utility as a practical metric for data quality that\ncan inform future data collection efforts. Furthermore, applying Indigenous ASR makes this issue especially acute. First, Pacific\nQuaSR yields the largest gains on Lelepa and Nguna, reducing languages (e.g., diverse Austronesian and Papuan families [20],\nWER by up to 4.01 absolute points and CER by up to 3.76 [21]) are not merely low-resource; they are distributionally\nabsolute points. In-depth analysis additionally reveals that highly distant from the Indo-European languages dominating\nthe proposed scores are indicative of sample quality in the modern speech foundation models [22], [23]. Second, Pacific\nlatent space. The contributions of this work are summarised corpora are collected from multiple legacy field linguistics and\nethnographic archives. The audio suffers from unstructured\nas follows:\nenvironmental degradation and conversational overlap [24],\n• This is the first study to systematically analyze data quality\nwhile\nthe transcriptions exhibit orthographic fluidity [4].\nfor Pacific Indigenous languages in the context of ASR\nCommonly\nused acoustic intelligibility estimators such as\nadaptation.\nSQUIM\nand\nSTOI\nprovide a practical means of approximating\n• QuaSR provides the first integration of data-centric\nlearning principles into a sample reweighting scheme for\n\n\fTABLE I: Data statistics across different languages.\nLanguage\n\nSamples\n\nDuration (H)\n\nAvg. (S)\n\nBislama\nNafsan\nLelepa\nNguna\n\n11,507\n9,226\n3,022\n1,115\n\n13.36\n14.71\n3.55\n1.02\n\n4.18\n5.74\n4.23\n3.29\n\nTotal\n\n23,870\n\n32.64\n\n4.92\n\nacoustic quality [11], [12]. Transcript quality is commonly evaluated through transcription consistency or reference-based error\nmeasures when repeated annotations or reference transcripts\nare available [10], [25]. Audio–text alignment constitutes a\nthird dimension, which measures whether a transcript and its\ncorresponding recording are mismatched or poorly segmented\nat the utterance level, and is generally estimated using forcedalignment tools that compute frame-level correspondence\nbetween the acoustic signal and its transcript [2]. Multilingual resources such as MMS make such forced-alignment\ndiagnostics feasible across many low-resource languages [2].\nWhilst each of these dimensions has been studied independently\nand provides useful evidence in its own right, they are rarely\nconsidered jointly, leaving a gap in our understanding of how\ntheir combination shapes data reliability. More importantly, how\nthese dimensions can be collectively applied to estimate data\nquality for Pacific Indigenous languages, and subsequently\nleveraged to improve ASR adaptation, remains an open\nquestion. These three dimensions together motivate a more\ncomprehensive and principled picture of data quality for lowresource ASR adaptation.\nIII. PACIFIC I NDIGENOUS S PEECH C ORPUS\n\n(A). The model-side learnability term is estimated from samplelevel loss values recorded during an unweighted baseline\ntraining run. QuaSR multiplies these two terms so that a\nsample receives high training influence only when it is both\nreliable in data quality and learnable for the current model.\nThe resulting sample utility is then incorporated in a soft loss\nweight for LoRA adaptation.\nA. Data Reliability\nData-side reliability estimates whether an utterance is a\nhigh-quality sample suitable for reliable supervision by capturing three complementary dimensions. Acoustic quality (Q),\nestimated using the SQUIM estimate of short-time objective\nintelligibility (STOI), measures whether the speech signal is\nsufficiently intelligible for ASR training [11], [12]. Transcript\nstability (T ) measures visible transcription irregularities in the\ntranscript, including markers of incomplete transcription, digit\ncharacters, and isolated non-lexical symbols. Audio–text alignment reliability (A), estimated from MMS forced-alignment\ndiagnostics, combines word-level alignment confidence with\nutterance-level CTC transcript agreement to measure whether\nthe transcript is well matched to the recording [2].\nAcoustic quality is measured using the reference-less SQUIM\nestimate of STOI [11], [12]. For each utterance, the pretrained\nSQUIM model takes the input waveform and predicts an\nSTOI score without requiring a clean reference signal. We\nuse this predicted STOI score as the raw acoustic-quality\nscore Q̃i . Low values indicate speech that is likely difficult to\nperceive because of noise, channel mismatch, or other acoustic\ndegradation, even when the transcript itself is valid. This\ncomponent therefore estimates the acoustic reliability of the\nrecording as a supervisory signal.\nTranscript stability penalizes visible transcription irregularities in the transcript without imposing a language-specific\n\u0012\n\u0013\ndictionary.\ndi + e i + u i\nT̃i = 1 − min 1,\n,\n(1)\nni\n\nWe use four labeled corpora derived from records curated\nby the Pacific and Regional Archive for Digital Sources in\nEndangered Cultures (PARADISEC): Bislama [26], Nafsan\n[27], Lelepa [28], and Nguna [29]. These datasets are annotated\nby community experts, providing valuable resources with\ntranscribed data for ASR. Bislama is an English-lexified\ncreole and one of Vanuatu’s official languages; Nafsan, Lelepa,\nand Nguna are Oceanic languages spoken in different regions where di , ei , and ui count digit characters, markers of\nof Vanuatu. The corpora differ in duration, elicitation style, incomplete transcription, and isolated non-lexical symbols,\nrecording condition, and transcript consistency, making them respectively, and ni is the number of non-space characters.\na useful testbed for data-quality-aware adaptation. Table I A lower T̃i therefore indicates that these counted irregularities\nsummarizes the corpus size and duration used in this study. The occupy a larger fraction of the transcript. Unicode letters and\ncorpora span 1.02–14.71 hours and 1,115–11,507 utterances. combining marks are not penalized, so the score does not treat\nNafsan has the longest total duration, with 14.71 hours of Indigenous orthography as noise.\nspeech, while Bislama contains the largest number of utterances,\nAudio–text alignment reliability is computed from MMS\nwith 11,507 samples. Nguna is the smallest corpus, containing forced-alignment diagnostics [2]. For utterance i, MMS aligns\n1.02 hours of speech and 1,115 samples. Average utterance the input waveform with the normalized transcript. Let Ji be\nduration is comparable across the four languages, ranging from th